The paper discusses algorithms for geometric problems such as triangulation and Delaunay triangulation, which are typically studied in the computational geometry (cs.CG) sub-category. The use of randomized algorithms and the focus on complexity analysis suggest that the paper could also fit in the data structures (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM) sub-categories. Additionally, the mention of the euclidean minimum spanning tree (EMST) suggests that numerical analysis (cs.NA) could be relevant. Finally, the paper's focus on graphs and their properties suggests that the graph theory (cs.GR) sub-category could also be a possibility.
